In the context of email communication, "cc" (carbon copy) and "bcc" (blind carbon copy) are terms used to indicate who should receive a copy of the email when it is sent.

"cc" is used when the sender wants to include one or more recipients in the copy of the message, and the recipients listed in the cc field will receive a copy of the email along with the primary recipients listed in the "to" field. This is useful when someone needs to be kept informed about the email exchange, but is not directly involved in the conversation.

"bcc," on the other hand, is used when the sender wants to keep the recipients listed in the bcc field private. When an email is sent with bcc, the recipients listed in the bcc field will receive a copy of the message, but their email addresses will not be visible to the primary recipients listed in the "to" field or the recipients listed in the cc field. This is useful when you want to send a group email to multiple recipients without revealing their email addresses to each other.

It's worth noting that the use of cc and bcc fields can be seen as a bit old-fashioned and impersonal in modern email communication. Many email clients now have a BCC field, which is used in the same way as the earlier "blind carbon copy" field.
